05226nam a22006375i 9780226522135DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017034940  a97802265221357 a10.7208/97802265221352doi  a(DE-B1597)549955  a(OCoLC)1030304690  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aKF4772b.H35 2018 4aKF4772b.H35 2018 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a343.7306/62231 aHamburger, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiberal Suppression :bSection 501(c)(3) and the Taxation of Speech /cPhilip Hamburger. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tONE. Conceptual Foundations -- tPART I. Group Speech and Liberal Fears -- tTWO. Idealistic Organizations in Politics -- tTHREE. Liberal Democratic Anxieties -- tPART II. The Liberal Assault -- tFOUR. Influence and Propaganda -- tFIVE. Segregation -- tSIX. Subversion -- tSEVEN. Political Theory -- tPART III. Unconstitutional -- tEIGHT. The Force of Law -- tNINE. First Amendment Principles -- tTEN. Licensing and Wholesale Suppression -- tELEVEN. Government Interests -- tTWELVE. Other Avenues for Speech -- tTHIRTEEN. Not Only Exemptions but Also Deductions -- tFOURTEEN. Distortions of Constitutional Doctrine -- tPART IV. Divided and Subdued -- tFIFTEEN. Rights of Associators and Associations -- tSIXTEEN. Fractions of Persons and Rights -- tSEVENTEEN. Government Homogenization of Public Opinion -- tEIGHTEEN. Contemporary Speech Restrictions -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the course of exempting religious, educational, and charitable organizations from federal income tax, section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code requires them to refrain from campaign speech and much speech to influence legislation. These speech restrictions have seemed merely technical adjustments, which prevent the political use of a tax subsidy. But the cultural and legal realities are more disturbing. Tracing the history of American liberalism, including theological liberalism and its expression in nativism, Hamburger shows the centrality of turbulent popular anxieties about the Catholic Church and other potentially orthodox institutions. He argues persuasively that such theopolitical fears about the political speech of churches and related organizations underlay the adoption, in 1934 and 1954, of section 501(c)(3)’s speech limits. He thereby shows that the speech restrictions have been part of a broad majority assault on minority rights and that they are grossly unconstitutional. Along the way, Hamburger explores the role of the Ku Klux Klan and other nativist organizations, the development of American theology, and the cultural foundations of liberal “democratic” political theory. He also traces important legal developments such as the specialization of speech rights and the use of law to homogenize beliefs. Ultimately, he examines a wide range of contemporary speech restrictions and the growing shallowness of public life in America. His account is an unflinching look at the complex history of American liberalism and at the implications for speech, the diversity of belief, and the nation’s future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCharity laws and legislationzUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxReligious aspects. 0aLiberalszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aReligion and lawzUnited States. 0aReligion and politicszUnited Stat